AI Friday Season 2 – Problem Statements 
Personalized Speech Recognition for Users with Speech Impairments 
PROBLEM STATEMENT 
Users with speech impairments such as stammering, dysarthria, aphasia, long pauses, incomplete commands, or 
vocal fatigue often face repeated failures when voice systems expect fluent, standard speech. For instance, users like 
Riya attempting critical tasks such as checking bank balances may be misunderstood, timed out, or forced to restart 
without a clear recovery path. This limits access to essential services and increases user effort, frustration, and 
dependency on assisted channels. Current systems rely heavily on generic speech models and often lack personalized 
learning, confirmation, flexible input, and graceful error recovery for non-standard speech patterns. The business 
impact includes loss of trust, increased support costs, accessibility gaps, and regulatory risk. The challenge is to design 
a personalized voice interaction experience that helps users with varied speech patterns complete tasks safely and 
confidently, even when recognition confidence is low or speech is interrupted. 
Data Considerations: 
Requires dysarthric and impaired speech datasets capturing diverse non-standard patterns and stammer variations in 
multiple languages; speaker-specific voice training data to enable personalization; data should include both controlled 
and real-world noisy samples to ensure robustness; volume should cover hundreds of hours to train adaptive models 
effectively; data privacy and consent compliance (e.g., GDPR) must be enforced; synthetic data generation using 
speech augmentation tools can supplement rare impairment types; preprocessing involves noise reduction, 
segmentation, and normalization to standardize inputs for model training. 
Consider using synthetic or anonymized data where appropriate. Ensure data quality and relevance to the problem 
context. 
SOLUTION EXPECTATIONS 
A user-friendly application demonstrating personalized voice interaction for users with speech impairments; adaptive 
learning that improves over repeated interactions; real-time transcription, confirmation, and correction feedback; 
flexible fallback options such as text, touch, or assisted confirmation; backend integration with APIs for task execution; 
measurable improvements using task completion rate, first-attempt success, retry count, clarification turns reduced, 
successful recovery from incomplete speech, and reduction in user effort; documentation mapping the solution to PAS 
901 principles including error recovery, user control, adaptive interaction, confirmation and clarity, discoverability, 
flexible input, and cognitive accessibility; demo scenarios covering stammering, long pauses, incomplete commands, 
low-confidence recognition, vocal fatigue, and noisy environments. 
Accessibility Impact: Benefits users with speech impairments, temporary voice changes, and fatigue-related speech 
variation by reducing misrecognition, timeout, and restart barriers. Expected outcome: users can complete sensitive 
tasks with greater independence, confidence, and dignity. 
Feel free to explore creative solutions that align with the problem context and objectives. 
